Crate root for `ctx-cage`, the sandboxing layer that bounds an autonomous agent run's blast radius on filesystem, host namespaces, and network — it no longer masks source or brokers tool calls (that moved to `ctx-context`'s hook-led context chain); the agent uses native Read/Edit inside the cage.

The file itself is just module wiring plus one constant: `pub const CAGE_RULES_MD: &str = include_str!("../assets/cage-rules.md")`. This embeds the agent doctrine text at compile time via `include_str!`, so the binary physically cannot build without `assets/cage-rules.md` present — moving or renaming that file breaks compilation, not just behavior. `CAGE_RULES_MD` is injected on every real `claude` launch via `--append-system-prompt-file`; whoever constructs that launch (see `cli`/`lifecycle`) must keep passing this constant, or the cage's safety doctrine silently stops reaching the agent.

Six submodules carry the actual logic: `bwrap` (constructs the `bwrap` sandbox invocation — namespaces, mounts, `--die-with-parent`, `no_new_privs`), `cli`, `error`, `lifecycle`, `proxy` (host-side process that terminates TLS to the real API and injects the API key, reached only via a bind-mounted UNIX socket so the raw key never enters the cage), and `runtime`. This root file carries no logic of its own beyond the doc comment's architecture summary, which is the authoritative statement of the current security model — cross-check it before changing any submodule's mount/network/namespace behavior, since drift between code and this comment is the main risk here. Notable stated gap: a seccomp filter is documented as a residual, not yet implemented.